Node.Notes: Two halves of this verse do not give expected contrasting parallel. May mean "the wicked hide violence in their words."
Literally "A fool of lips," which seems to mean a "foolish talker."
As this line is identical to second line of v. 8, some choose to follow the LXX and read something like "but the one who reproves boldly makes peace."
Identical to second line of v. 6.
Covering in sense of "forgiving/overlooking" rather than in sense of "concealing."
Either the person will have a long and happy life or the person himself is able to lead others to life by instructing them.
Uncertain. Apparently the one who conceals = subject and lying lips (= liar?) = predicate. Some ignore parallelism: the concealer of hatred with lying lips and the slanderer, he [is] a fool.
Probably carries over "pleasure" from first half. So wisdom is "pleasure" for sensible people in contrast to foolish people who find pleasure in doing evil.
